{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"If you take 10,000 people at random, 9,999 have something in common:"},{"time":6000,"text":"their interests in business lie on or near the Earth's surface."},{"time":11000,"text":"The odd one out is an astronomer, and I am one of that strange breed."},{"time":15000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":16000,"text":"My talk will be in two parts. I'll talk first as an astronomer,"},{"time":21000,"text":"and then as a worried member of the human race."},{"time":25000,"text":"But let's start off by remembering that Darwin showed"},{"time":30000,"text":"how we're the outcome of four billion years of evolution."},{"time":34000,"text":"And what we try to do in astronomy and cosmology"},{"time":37000,"text":"is to go back before Darwin's simple beginning,"},{"time":40000,"text":"to set our Earth in a cosmic context."}]},{"cues":[{"time":44000,"text":"And let me just run through a few slides."},{"time":47000,"text":"This was the impact that happened last week on a comet."},{"time":52000,"text":"If they'd sent a nuke, it would have been rather more spectacular"},{"time":54000,"text":"than what actually happened last Monday."},{"time":57000,"text":"So that's another project for NASA."},{"time":59000,"text":"That's Mars from the European Mars Express, and at New Year."},{"time":64000,"text":"This artist's impression turned into reality"},{"time":69000,"text":"when a parachute landed on Titan, Saturn's giant moon."},{"time":73000,"text":"It landed on the surface. This is pictures taken on the way down."},{"time":77000,"text":"That looks like a coastline."},{"time":78000,"text":"It is indeed, but the ocean is liquid methane --"},{"time":81000,"text":"the temperature minus 170 degrees centigrade."},{"time":86000,"text":"If we go beyond our solar system,"},{"time":88000,"text":"we've learned that the stars aren't twinkly points of light."},{"time":92000,"text":"Each one is like a sun with a retinue of planets orbiting around it."},{"time":97000,"text":"And we can see places where stars are forming,"},{"time":100000,"text":"like the Eagle Nebula. We see stars dying."},{"time":103000,"text":"In six billion years, the sun will look like that."},{"time":106000,"text":"And some stars die spectacularly in a supernova explosion,"},{"time":110000,"text":"leaving remnants like that."}]},{"cues":[{"time":112000,"text":"On a still bigger scale, we see entire galaxies of stars."},{"time":116000,"text":"We see entire ecosystems where gas is being recycled."},{"time":119000,"text":"And to the cosmologist,"},{"time":121000,"text":"these galaxies are just the atoms, as it were, of the large-scale universe."},{"time":127000,"text":"This picture shows a patch of sky"},{"time":130000,"text":"so small that it would take about 100 patches like it"},{"time":133000,"text":"to cover the full moon in the sky."},{"time":136000,"text":"Through a small telescope, this would look quite blank,"},{"time":138000,"text":"but you see here hundreds of little, faint smudges."},{"time":142000,"text":"Each is a galaxy, fully like ours or Andromeda,"},{"time":146000,"text":"which looks so small and faint because its light"},{"time":148000,"text":"has taken 10 billion light-years to get to us."},{"time":152000,"text":"The stars in those galaxies probably don't have planets around them."},{"time":157000,"text":"There's scant chance of life there -- that's because there's been no time"},{"time":160000,"text":"for the nuclear fusion in stars to make silicon and carbon and iron,"},{"time":166000,"text":"the building blocks of planets and of life."},{"time":170000,"text":"We believe that all of this emerged from a Big Bang --"},{"time":176000,"text":"a hot, dense state. So how did that amorphous Big Bang"},{"time":180000,"text":"turn into our complex cosmos?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":182000,"text":"I'm going to show you a movie simulation"},{"time":185000,"text":"16 powers of 10 faster than real time,"},{"time":187000,"text":"which shows a patch of the universe where the expansions have subtracted out."},{"time":191000,"text":"But you see, as time goes on in gigayears at the bottom,"},{"time":195000,"text":"you will see structures evolve as gravity feeds"},{"time":198000,"text":"on small, dense irregularities, and structures develop."},{"time":202000,"text":"And we'll end up after 13 billion years"},{"time":204000,"text":"with something looking rather like our own universe."},{"time":211000,"text":"And we compare simulated universes like that --"},{"time":214000,"text":"I'll show you a better simulation at the end of my talk --"},{"time":216000,"text":"with what we actually see in the sky."},{"time":220000,"text":"Well, we can trace things back to the earlier stages of the Big Bang,"},{"time":226000,"text":"but we still don't know what banged and why it banged."}]},{"cues":[{"time":230000,"text":"That's a challenge for 21st-century science."},{"time":235000,"text":"If my research group had a logo, it would be this picture here:"},{"time":238000,"text":"an ouroboros, where you see the micro-world on the left --"},{"time":243000,"text":"the world of the quantum -- and on the right"},{"time":246000,"text":"the large-scale universe of planets, stars and galaxies."},{"time":251000,"text":"We know our universes are united though --"},{"time":253000,"text":"links between left and right."},{"time":255000,"text":"The everyday world is determined by atoms,"},{"time":257000,"text":"how they stick together to make molecules."},{"time":259000,"text":"Stars are fueled by how the nuclei in those atoms react together."},{"time":265000,"text":"And, as we've learned in the last few years, galaxies are held together"},{"time":268000,"text":"by the gravitational pull of so-called dark matter:"},{"time":271000,"text":"particles in huge swarms, far smaller even than atomic nuclei."},{"time":277000,"text":"But we'd like to know the synthesis symbolized at the very top."},{"time":283000,"text":"The micro-world of the quantum is understood."},{"time":286000,"text":"On the right hand side, gravity holds sway. Einstein explained that."},{"time":291000,"text":"But the unfinished business for 21st-century science"},{"time":294000,"text":"is to link together cosmos and micro-world"},{"time":296000,"text":"with a unified theory -- symbolized, as it were, gastronomically"},{"time":300000,"text":"at the top of that picture. (Laughter)"},{"time":302000,"text":"And until we have that synthesis,"},{"time":304000,"text":"we won't be able to understand the very beginning of our universe"},{"time":307000,"text":"because when our universe was itself the size of an atom,"},{"time":310000,"text":"quantum effects could shake everything."}]},{"cues":[{"time":313000,"text":"And so we need a theory that unifies the very large and the very small,"},{"time":317000,"text":"which we don't yet have."},{"time":320000,"text":"One idea, incidentally --"},{"time":322000,"text":"and I had this hazard sign to say I'm going to speculate from now on --"},{"time":327000,"text":"is that our Big Bang was not the only one."},{"time":329000,"text":"One idea is that our three-dimensional universe"},{"time":333000,"text":"may be embedded in a high-dimensional space,"},{"time":335000,"text":"just as you can imagine on these sheets of paper."},{"time":338000,"text":"You can imagine ants on one of them"},{"time":340000,"text":"thinking it's a two-dimensional universe,"},{"time":342000,"text":"not being aware of another population of ants on the other."},{"time":344000,"text":"So there could be another universe just a millimeter away from ours,"},{"time":348000,"text":"but we're not aware of it because that millimeter"},{"time":351000,"text":"is measured in some fourth spatial dimension,"},{"time":353000,"text":"and we're imprisoned in our three."},{"time":355000,"text":"And so we believe that there may be a lot more to physical reality"},{"time":360000,"text":"than what we've normally called our universe --"},{"time":362000,"text":"the aftermath of our Big Bang. And here's another picture."},{"time":365000,"text":"Bottom right depicts our universe,"},{"time":367000,"text":"which on the horizon is not beyond that,"},{"time":369000,"text":"but even that is just one bubble, as it were, in some vaster reality."},{"time":374000,"text":"Many people suspect that just as we've gone from believing"},{"time":377000,"text":"in one solar system to zillions of solar systems,"},{"time":381000,"text":"one galaxy to many galaxies,"},{"time":383000,"text":"we have to go to many Big Bangs from one Big Bang,"},{"time":387000,"text":"perhaps these many Big Bangs displaying"},{"time":389000,"text":"an immense variety of properties."}]},{"cues":[{"time":391000,"text":"Well, let's go back to this picture."},{"time":393000,"text":"There's one challenge symbolized at the top,"},{"time":396000,"text":"but there's another challenge to science symbolized at the bottom."},{"time":400000,"text":"You want to not only synthesize the very large and the very small,"},{"time":403000,"text":"but we want to understand the very complex."},{"time":406000,"text":"And the most complex things are ourselves,"},{"time":408000,"text":"midway between atoms and stars."},{"time":410000,"text":"We depend on stars to make the atoms we're made of."},{"time":412000,"text":"We depend on chemistry to determine our complex structure."},{"time":418000,"text":"We clearly have to be large, compared to atoms,"},{"time":421000,"text":"to have layer upon layer of complex structure."},{"time":423000,"text":"We clearly have to be small, compared to stars and planets --"},{"time":426000,"text":"otherwise we'd be crushed by gravity. And in fact, we are midway."},{"time":430000,"text":"It would take as many human bodies to make up the sun"},{"time":432000,"text":"as there are atoms in each of us."},{"time":434000,"text":"The geometric mean of the mass of a proton"},{"time":436000,"text":"and the mass of the sun is 50 kilograms,"},{"time":439000,"text":"within a factor of two of the mass of each person here."},{"time":442000,"text":"Well, most of you anyway."},{"time":443000,"text":"The science of complexity is probably the greatest challenge of all,"},{"time":448000,"text":"greater than that of the very small on the left"},{"time":450000,"text":"and the very large on the right."},{"time":453000,"text":"And it's this science,"},{"time":455000,"text":"which is not only enlightening our understanding of the biological world,"},{"time":459000,"text":"but also transforming our world faster than ever."},{"time":463000,"text":"And more than that, it's engendering new kinds of change."}]},{"cues":[{"time":467000,"text":"And I now move on to the second part of my talk,"},{"time":472000,"text":"and the book \"Our Final Century\" was mentioned."},{"time":476000,"text":"If I was not a self-effacing Brit, I would mention the book myself,"},{"time":480000,"text":"and I would add that it's available in paperback."}]},{"cues":[{"time":483000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":486000,"text":"And in America it was called \"Our Final Hour\""},{"time":489000,"text":"because Americans like instant gratification."}]},{"cues":[{"time":491000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":493000,"text":"But my theme is that in this century,"},{"time":496000,"text":"not only has science changed the world faster than ever,"},{"time":499000,"text":"but in new and different ways."},{"time":502000,"text":"Targeted drugs, genetic modification, artificial intelligence,"},{"time":506000,"text":"perhaps even implants into our brains,"},{"time":508000,"text":"may change human beings themselves. And human beings,"},{"time":511000,"text":"their physique and character, has not changed for thousands of years."},{"time":515000,"text":"It may change this century."},{"time":517000,"text":"It's new in our history."},{"time":519000,"text":"And the human impact on the global environment -- greenhouse warming,"},{"time":522000,"text":"mass extinctions and so forth -- is unprecedented, too."},{"time":526000,"text":"And so, this makes this coming century a challenge."},{"time":531000,"text":"Bio- and cybertechnologies are environmentally benign"},{"time":534000,"text":"in that they offer marvelous prospects,"},{"time":536000,"text":"while, nonetheless, reducing pressure on energy and resources."},{"time":540000,"text":"But they will have a dark side."},{"time":543000,"text":"In our interconnected world, novel technology could empower"},{"time":547000,"text":"just one fanatic,"},{"time":549000,"text":"or some weirdo with a mindset of those who now design computer viruses,"},{"time":553000,"text":"to trigger some kind on disaster."},{"time":555000,"text":"Indeed, catastrophe could arise simply from technical misadventure --"},{"time":559000,"text":"error rather than terror."},{"time":561000,"text":"And even a tiny probability of catastrophe is unacceptable"},{"time":566000,"text":"when the downside could be of global consequence."}]},{"cues":[{"time":571000,"text":"In fact, some years ago, Bill Joy wrote an article"},{"time":575000,"text":"expressing tremendous concern about robots taking us over, etc."},{"time":579000,"text":"I don't go along with all that,"},{"time":580000,"text":"but it's interesting that he had a simple solution."},{"time":582000,"text":"It was what he called \"fine-grained relinquishment.\""},{"time":585000,"text":"He wanted to give up the dangerous kind of science"},{"time":588000,"text":"and keep the good bits. Now, that's absurdly naive for two reasons."},{"time":592000,"text":"First, any scientific discovery has benign consequences"},{"time":596000,"text":"as well as dangerous ones."},{"time":598000,"text":"And also, when a scientist makes a discovery,"},{"time":601000,"text":"he or she normally has no clue what the applications are going to be."},{"time":605000,"text":"And so what this means is that we have to accept the risks"},{"time":610000,"text":"if we are going to enjoy the benefits of science."},{"time":614000,"text":"We have to accept that there will be hazards."},{"time":617000,"text":"And I think we have to go back to what happened in the post-War era,"},{"time":623000,"text":"post-World War II, when the nuclear scientists"},{"time":626000,"text":"who'd been involved in making the atomic bomb,"},{"time":628000,"text":"in many cases were concerned that they should do all they could"},{"time":632000,"text":"to alert the world to the dangers."}]},{"cues":[{"time":634000,"text":"And they were inspired not by the young Einstein,"},{"time":638000,"text":"who did the great work in relativity, but by the old Einstein,"},{"time":643000,"text":"the icon of poster and t-shirt,"},{"time":646000,"text":"who failed in his scientific efforts to unify the physical laws."},{"time":650000,"text":"He was premature. But he was a moral compass --"},{"time":653000,"text":"an inspiration to scientists who were concerned with arms control."},{"time":658000,"text":"And perhaps the greatest living person"},{"time":660000,"text":"is someone I'm privileged to know, Joe Rothblatt."},{"time":663000,"text":"Equally untidy office there, as you can see."},{"time":666000,"text":"He's 96 years old, and he founded the Pugwash movement."},{"time":670000,"text":"He persuaded Einstein, as his last act,"},{"time":672000,"text":"to sign the famous memorandum of Bertrand Russell."},{"time":675000,"text":"And he sets an example of the concerned scientist."},{"time":680000,"text":"And I think to harness science optimally,"},{"time":683000,"text":"to choose which doors to open and which to leave closed,"},{"time":686000,"text":"we need latter-day counterparts of people like Joseph Rothblatt."}]},{"cues":[{"time":691000,"text":"We need not just campaigning physicists,"},{"time":693000,"text":"but we need biologists, computer experts"},{"time":695000,"text":"and environmentalists as well."},{"time":698000,"text":"And I think academics and independent entrepreneurs"},{"time":701000,"text":"have a special obligation because they have more freedom"},{"time":703000,"text":"than those in government service,"},{"time":705000,"text":"or company employees subject to commercial pressure."},{"time":708000,"text":"I wrote my book, \"Our Final Century,\" as a scientist,"},{"time":713000,"text":"just a general scientist. But there's one respect, I think,"},{"time":716000,"text":"in which being a cosmologist offered a special perspective,"},{"time":720000,"text":"and that's that it offers an awareness of the immense future."},{"time":724000,"text":"The stupendous time spans of the evolutionary past"},{"time":727000,"text":"are now part of common culture --"},{"time":730000,"text":"outside the American Bible Belt, anyway --"},{"time":733000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":734000,"text":"but most people, even those who are familiar with evolution,"},{"time":738000,"text":"aren't mindful that even more time lies ahead."}]},{"cues":[{"time":742000,"text":"The sun has been shining for four and a half billion years,"},{"time":745000,"text":"but it'll be another six billion years before its fuel runs out."},{"time":749000,"text":"On that schematic picture, a sort of time-lapse picture, we're halfway."},{"time":755000,"text":"And it'll be another six billion before that happens,"},{"time":760000,"text":"and any remaining life on Earth is vaporized."},{"time":765000,"text":"There's an unthinking tendency to imagine that humans will be there,"},{"time":768000,"text":"experiencing the sun's demise,"},{"time":770000,"text":"but any life and intelligence that exists then"},{"time":773000,"text":"will be as different from us as we are from bacteria."},{"time":777000,"text":"The unfolding of intelligence and complexity"},{"time":779000,"text":"still has immensely far to go, here on Earth and probably far beyond."},{"time":785000,"text":"So we are still at the beginning of the emergence of complexity"},{"time":788000,"text":"in our Earth and beyond."},{"time":791000,"text":"If you represent the Earth's lifetime by a single year,"},{"time":795000,"text":"say from January when it was made to December,"},{"time":798000,"text":"the 21st-century would be a quarter of a second in June --"},{"time":804000,"text":"a tiny fraction of the year."},{"time":807000,"text":"But even in this concertinaed cosmic perspective,"},{"time":811000,"text":"our century is very, very special,"},{"time":814000,"text":"the first when humans can change themselves and their home planet."}]},{"cues":[{"time":819000,"text":"As I should have shown this earlier,"},{"time":822000,"text":"it will not be humans who witness the end point of the sun;"},{"time":825000,"text":"it will be creatures as different from us as we are from bacteria."},{"time":830000,"text":"When Einstein died in 1955,"},{"time":833000,"text":"one striking tribute to his global status was this cartoon"},{"time":836000,"text":"by Herblock in the Washington Post."},{"time":838000,"text":"The plaque reads, \"Albert Einstein lived here.\""},{"time":842000,"text":"And I'd like to end with a vignette, as it were, inspired by this image."},{"time":846000,"text":"We've been familiar for 40 years with this image:"},{"time":852000,"text":"the fragile beauty of land, ocean and clouds,"},{"time":855000,"text":"contrasted with the sterile moonscape"},{"time":857000,"text":"on which the astronauts left their footprints."},{"time":861000,"text":"But let's suppose some aliens had been watching our pale blue dot"},{"time":865000,"text":"in the cosmos from afar, not just for 40 years,"},{"time":869000,"text":"but for the entire 4.5 billion-year history of our Earth."},{"time":874000,"text":"What would they have seen?"},{"time":876000,"text":"Over nearly all that immense time,"},{"time":878000,"text":"Earth's appearance would have changed very gradually."},{"time":881000,"text":"The only abrupt worldwide change"},{"time":883000,"text":"would have been major asteroid impacts or volcanic super-eruptions."},{"time":889000,"text":"Apart from those brief traumas, nothing happens suddenly."}]},{"cues":[{"time":893000,"text":"The continental landmasses drifted around."},{"time":896000,"text":"Ice cover waxed and waned."},{"time":898000,"text":"Successions of new species emerged, evolved and became extinct."},{"time":902000,"text":"But in just a tiny sliver of the Earth's history,"},{"time":906000,"text":"the last one-millionth part, a few thousand years,"},{"time":910000,"text":"the patterns of vegetation altered much faster than before."},{"time":913000,"text":"This signaled the start of agriculture."},{"time":916000,"text":"Change has accelerated as human populations rose."},{"time":920000,"text":"Then other things happened even more abruptly."},{"time":922000,"text":"Within just 50 years --"},{"time":924000,"text":"that's one hundredth of one millionth of the Earth's age --"},{"time":928000,"text":"the amount of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere started to rise,"},{"time":932000,"text":"and ominously fast."}]},{"cues":[{"time":934000,"text":"The planet became an intense emitter of radio waves --"},{"time":936000,"text":"the total output from all TV and cell phones"},{"time":940000,"text":"and radar transmissions. And something else happened."},{"time":943000,"text":"Metallic objects -- albeit very small ones, a few tons at most --"},{"time":948000,"text":"escaped into orbit around the Earth."},{"time":951000,"text":"Some journeyed to the moons and planets."},{"time":953000,"text":"A race of advanced extraterrestrials"},{"time":955000,"text":"watching our solar system from afar"},{"time":958000,"text":"could confidently predict Earth's final doom in another six billion years."},{"time":963000,"text":"But could they have predicted this unprecedented spike"},{"time":967000,"text":"less than halfway through the Earth's life?"},{"time":970000,"text":"These human-induced alterations"},{"time":972000,"text":"occupying overall less than a millionth of the elapsed lifetime"},{"time":976000,"text":"and seemingly occurring with runaway speed?"},{"time":979000,"text":"If they continued their vigil,"},{"time":981000,"text":"what might these hypothetical aliens witness"},{"time":983000,"text":"in the next hundred years?"},{"time":986000,"text":"Will some spasm foreclose Earth's future?"},{"time":989000,"text":"Or will the biosphere stabilize?"},{"time":992000,"text":"Or will some of the metallic objects launched from the Earth"},{"time":995000,"text":"spawn new oases, a post-human life elsewhere?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":999000,"text":"The science done by the young Einstein will continue"},{"time":1002000,"text":"as long as our civilization, but for civilization to survive,"},{"time":1007000,"text":"we'll need the wisdom of the old Einstein --"},{"time":1009000,"text":"humane, global and farseeing."},{"time":1011000,"text":"And whatever happens in this uniquely crucial century"},{"time":1016000,"text":"will resonate into the remote future and perhaps far beyond the Earth,"},{"time":1022000,"text":"far beyond the Earth as depicted here."},{"time":1024000,"text":"Thank you very much."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1026000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}